Library/computation engine for planar geometry

Notes: The calculations herein depend on the assumption of general position; that is, no two points
have the same x-coord (equivalently, that no two points lie on the same vertical line), and that no three points are colinear.

Header Files:
helper.h - Contains useful functions for reading/printing input/output
point.h - Point object which defines a point in the plane
line.h - Line object which defines a non-vertical line in the plane
triangle.h - Triangle object which defines a triangle in the plane
edge.h - Edge object which defines one edge of a polygon in the plane
polygon.h - Polygon object which defines a polygon in the plane (either by a cyclic order
of vertices, or by the set of edges)
pointset.h - Pointset object which is a set of points

Desmos bridge
-------------
A local bridge page is available at `tools/desmos-bridge/index.html`.

Polygon schema format used for import/export:
`{"type":"polygon","id":"poly1","points":[[x1,y1],[x2,y2],...]}`

Triangulation schema format used for import/export:
`{"type":"triangulation","id":"poly1_triangulation","polygons":[{"type":"polygon","points":[[x1,y1],[x2,y2],[x3,y3]]},...]}`

In the CLI (`main`), option 6 exports the latest stored polygon to:
`tools/desmos-bridge/polygon-export.json`
and attempts to open the bridge page in your default browser.

`rand_poly_gen_driver` exports both:
- `tools/desmos-bridge/polygon-export.json`
- `tools/desmos-bridge/triangulation-export.json`

Bridge import behavior:
- Polygon and triangulation imports are manual (file picker or explicit endpoint URL).
- There is no automatic fetch/import on page load.
- Triangulations are rendered as a list of polygons in one Desmos expression.

If the automatic browser launch does not work:
1. Manually open `tools/desmos-bridge/index.html` in a browser.
2. Use the file picker to import `tools/desmos-bridge/polygon-export.json`.
3. Import `tools/desmos-bridge/triangulation-export.json` to overlay the triangulation.

Tip: if your system opens a file manager instead of a browser, opening
`index.html` directly from the browser (File -> Open File) is the most reliable fallback.


TDD test suite
--------------
A growing TDD-style validation suite lives under `testing/`.

Current coverage:
- `Point::is_between`
- `collides(...)` helper function
- `is_inside(...)` helper functions
- `Triangle::` geometry calculations 

Run with:
`make test-suite`

Debug logging tags
------------------
Debug logging is now configured at runtime (in addition to build-time `-DDEBUG` defaults).

Supported runtime inputs:
- CLI: `--debug-tags=poly.gen,poly.validate`
- ENV: `GEOM_DEBUG_TAGS=poly.gen,poly.validate`
- Optional prefix behavior: `--debug-match-prefix=true|false` or `GEOM_DEBUG_MATCH_PREFIX=true|false`

Behavior:
- Debug logs are disabled when `debug_enabled` is false.
- `*` enables all tags.
- A configured tag matches either exact tags or (by default) nested tags via prefix matching.
  Example: `poly` matches `poly.gen` when prefix matching is enabled.

Examples:
- Focus on polygon generation logs only:
  `./build/development/debug/rand_poly_gen_driver --debug-tags=poly.gen`
- Enable all debug logs:
  `./build/development/debug/main --debug-tags=*`
- Use env vars for one shell session:
  `GEOM_DEBUG_TAGS=poly.validate ./build/development/debug/main`

Backward compatibility:
- Existing untagged `DBG(...)` callsites are mapped to the fallback tag `legacy`.
- With `-DDEBUG`, the default enabled tag is `legacy` to preserve previous behavior.


Adding new debug statements
---------------------------
Use tagged logging for all new debug output so logs can be filtered by subsystem at runtime.

Recommended tag style:
- Use dotted namespaces by area, e.g. `poly.gen`, `poly.validate`, `triangulate.ear`.
- Keep tags stable once introduced so scripts and workflows remain predictable.

How to log:
- Preferred for new code: `DBG_TAG("poly.gen", "generated vertex " << v.to_string() << "\n");`
- Legacy-compatible macro still works: `DBG("old debug message\n");` (maps to `legacy`).

How filtering works:
- `--debug-tags=poly.gen` enables exact `poly.gen` plus children like `poly.gen.step1` when prefix matching is enabled (default).
- `--debug-tags=*` enables every tag.
- `--debug-match-prefix=false` switches matching to exact-only.

Example workflow while adding logs:
1. Add a new statement with `DBG_TAG("poly.validate", ... )` near the code path you are investigating.
2. Build debug binaries: `make development-debug`.
3. Run with focused logging: `./build/development/debug/main --debug-tags=poly.validate`.
4. If you need broader scope temporarily: `--debug-tags=poly`.

Environment-variable equivalents:
- `GEOM_DEBUG_TAGS=poly.validate`
- `GEOM_DEBUG_MATCH_PREFIX=true|false`
- Optional global switch: `GEOM_DEBUG=true|false`

Build system (Makefile) usage and maintenance
--------------------------------------------
The project Makefile is designed to support three build configurations and to
automatically track header dependencies.

Common targets:
- `make development-normal`
  - Builds all executables under `build/development/normal/` with optimized flags
    suitable for regular local runs.
- `make development-debug`
  - Builds all executables under `build/development/debug/` with debug flags
    (`-g -O0 -DDEBUG`).
- `make release`
  - Builds all executables under `build/release/` with optimized flags.
- `make development`
  - Builds both normal and debug development variants.
- `make all`
  - Builds development + release outputs.
- `make test-suite`
  - Builds/runs the `tester` executable from development-normal.
- `make clean`
  - Removes all build outputs.
- `make help`
  - Prints quick maintenance guidance.

Current executable outputs:
- `build/development/normal/main`
- `build/development/normal/rand_poly_gen_driver`
- `build/development/normal/driver`
- `build/development/normal/tester`
(and matching paths in `build/development/debug/` and `build/release/`).

How automatic dependency generation works:
- Each compilation emits a dependency file beside its object file using
  compiler flags `-MMD -MP`.
- Example: building `build/development/debug/helper.o` also produces
  `build/development/debug/helper.d`.
- The Makefile includes generated `.d` files, so changing a header (or changing
  `#include` relationships) automatically triggers recompilation of affected
  objects on the next `make`.
- You do NOT need to manually write header prerequisites in the Makefile.

What to update when adding code:
1) Add a new shared class/algorithm (`.cc` + `.h`) used by executables
- Add the new `.cc` file to `COMMON_SRCS`.
- Include its header from relevant sources as usual.
- No manual dependency rule updates are needed.

2) Add a new executable
- Add the executable name to `EXES`.
- Add a source mapping variable in the form:
  - `EXE_<name>_SRCS := path/to/entry_or_harness.cc [more .cc files if needed]`
- After that, `make development-normal`, `make development-debug`, and
  `make release` will all build it automatically in their respective output
  directories.

3) Add more source files for an existing executable
- Update `EXE_<name>_SRCS` for that executable with the new `.cc` file(s).
- If the new file is shared by all executables instead, place it in
  `COMMON_SRCS`.

Recommended workflow after Makefile edits:
1. `make clean`
2. `make development-normal`
3. `make development-debug`
4. `make release`
5. Optional dependency sanity check:
   - `touch <some_header>.h`
   - `make -n build/development/debug/<some_executable>`
   - Confirm dependent objects are listed for rebuild.

Troubleshooting tips:
- If a new executable is not being built, verify both:
  - It appears in `EXES`.
  - A correctly named `EXE_<name>_SRCS` variable exists.
- If a source file fails to compile due to path errors, verify the path is
  relative to the repository root (same convention as other `.cc` entries).
- If make behavior seems stale, run `make clean` once to reset generated
  objects/dependency files.
